{{Infobox cycling race report | name =Men's time trial | image =2010 World Championships - Time Trial Medallists - David Millar, Fabian Cancellara, Tony Martin, jjron, 30.09.10.jpg | image_caption =Medallists: [[David Millar]], [[Fabian Cancellara]], & [[Tony Martin (cyclist)|Tony Martin]] | image_size =250 | series = [[2010 UCI Road World Championships]] | race_no = | series_no = | date = September 30, 2010 | stages = 1 | distance = 45.6 | unit = km | time = 58' 09.19" | speed = 47.048 | type = medals | first = [[Fabian Cancellara]] | first_nat = Switzerland | first_natvar = | first_team = | second = [[David Millar]] | second_nat = Great Britain | second_natvar = | second_team = | third = [[Tony Martin (cyclist)|Tony Martin]] | third_nat = Germany | third_natvar = | third_team = | previous = [[2009 UCI Road World Championships – Men's time trial|2009]] | next = [[2011 UCI Road World Championships – Men's time trial|2011]] }} {{2010 UCI Road World Championships}} [[File:2010 Fabian Cancellara, Cyclist, World Championship Race Geelong Aus, jjron, 30.09.10.jpg|thumb|right|[[Fabian Cancellara]] minutes before claiming a record fourth world title in the time trial race]] The '''Men's time trial''' of the [[2010 UCI Road World Championships]] cycling event took place on 30 September in [[Melbourne]] ([[Geelong, Victoria|Geelong]]), [[Australia]], the first time in [[UCI Road World Championships|the event's]] 77 times that it has been held in Australia.
[[Fabian Cancellara]] defended his title, and in doing so, clinched a record fourth time trial world championship, recording a time more than a minute faster than any of his rivals. [[Great Britain]]'s [[David Millar]] took silver, with [[Germany]]'s [[Tony Martin (cyclist)|Tony Martin]] claiming bronze. The two Australian entrants, [[Richie Porte]] and [[Michael Rogers (cyclist)|Michael Rogers]], came in fourth and fifth respectively in their home country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/cycling/9046839.stm|title=Fabian Cancellara beats David Millar to time trial gold|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=30 September 2010|accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref>
==Route== The riders completed two laps on an up-and-downhill 22.7&nbsp;km course for a total length of 45.6&nbsp;km.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.melbourne2010.com.au/default.aspx?s=geelong-time-trial-flash|title=Men's time trial course|work=melbourne2010.com|publisher=melbourne2010.com|accessdate=7 September 2010}}</ref>
