{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{Infobox Stadium | name = Old Recreation Ground | nickname = The Rec | image = | fullname = The Old Recreation Ground | location = [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Hanley]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[England]] | coordinates = {{coord|53|01|38.16|N|2|10|32.88|W}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1913 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = 1950 | demolished = 1950 | owner = | operator = | surface = [[Grass]] | construction_cost = | architect = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | project_manager = | main_contractors = | former_names = | tenants = [[Port Vale F.C.]] (1913–1950) | capacity = 20,000 | dimensions = 110 by 70 yards | scoreboard = }}
The '''Old Recreation Ground''' was a football stadium, located in [[Hanley, Staffordshire|Hanley]], [[Stoke-on-Trent]] and home to [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] for almost 40 years. The Rec had been Vale's home between 1913 and 1950 and was the sixth ground the club used.<ref name="Port-Vale.co.uk">{{cite web |url=http://www.port-vale.co.uk/page/ValePark/0,,10381,00.html |title=Port-Vale.co.uk: Vale Park |accessdate=18 December 2008|work=Port-Vale.co.uk}}</ref>
==Structure and facilities== [[File:The Old Recreation Ground attendances.JPG|thumb|right|400px|Average attendances, 1913–[[1949–50 Port Vale F.C. season|1950]].]]
The stadium was in rather bad condition, especially following years of neglect during [[World War II]]. The dressing rooms were bare, there were no toilet facilities throughout the entire ground, and [[Racing Homer|racing pigeon]]s were kept by ''[[The Sentinel (Staffordshire)|The Sentinel]]'' and a number of supporters so as to relay the scoreline to different parts of the city.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=Jeff|title=Port Vale Tales: A Collection Of Stories, Anecdotes And Memories|publisher=Witan Books|date=December 1991|pages=274|isbn=0-9508981-6-3}}</ref>
==History== [[Port Vale F.C.]] opened the ground in 1913, and six years later were admitted into the [[English Football League]]. The visit of [[Potteries derby]] rivals [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke]] on 6 March 1920 saw a crowd of 22,697 turn up to see an away victory.<ref name="rdd"/> Other big matches for Port Vale went more favourably in later years though, as they drew 2–2 with [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the [[FA Cup]] on 29 January 1927 and beat [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] 2–0 on 13 January 1936, again in the FA Cup.<ref name="rdd"/>
Port Vale were forced to sell the land to the city council, under the chairmanship of Tom W.Flint after suffering a financial crisis, they received £13,500.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kent|first=Jeff|title=Port Vale Personalities|publisher=Witan Books|page=103|date=1996|isbn=0-9529152-0-0|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Port-Vale-Personalities-Jeff-Kent/dp/0952915200}}</ref> This came after the club's president Major William Huntbach died in 1943, leaving £3,000 of loans to be repaid to his estate.<ref name="sixty">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisstaffordshire.co.uk/news/Port-Vale-glorious-years-Vale-Park/article-2561505-detail/article.html|title=Port Vale: 60-years ago today, Vale came back home to play|last=Sherwin|first=Phil|date=24 August 2010|work=The Sentinel|accessdate=24 August 2010}}</ref> The council initially refused to allow the club to play at their ground, but eventually relented for rent of £400 a year.<ref name="sixty" /> In 1950, the city council decided to construct a [[Potteries Shopping Centre|shopping centre]] on the site forcing the club to move to their current home of [[Vale Park]]. Ironically the club raised £50,000 to construct the new stadium, leading some to question why the directors did not simply attempt to raise a relatively much smaller sum of £3,000 in order to pay off the Huntbach family.<ref name="if">''What If There Had Been No Port In The Vale?: Startling Port Vale Stories!'' (Witan Books, 2011, {{ISBN|978-0-9529152-8-7}})</ref> The final match at the Old Recreation Ground was described as an "uninspiring finale" as Vale lost 1–0 to [[Aldershot F.C.|Aldershot]] in front of a crowd of 9,645 on 22 April 1950.<ref name="rdd">{{cite news|last1=Ault|first1=Richard|title=Rec was ‘den of old-style football without any frills’|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/news/history/port-vales-last-ever-game-462190|accessdate=16 September 2017|work=Stoke Sentinel|date=12 September 2017}}</ref>
